      "instruction": {
        "type": "prompt",
        "text": "Ask if the patient has any major medical conditions \nthe clinic should know about. A brief overview is \nsufficient — the full history will be collected via \nintake forms and at the first visit.\n\nSay something like: \"Last one on the new patient side \n— do you have any major medical conditions the doctor \nshould know about? Things like diabetes, heart \nconditions, asthma, surgeries — just the highlights.\"\n\nIf the user lists conditions: Acknowledge them: \"Got \nit — I've noted those down. The doctor will go into \nmore detail at your visit.\"\n\nIf the user says none or \"I'm healthy\": \"Great to \nhear! We'll still do a full review at your first \nvisit, but that's good to know.\"\n\nIf the user gives a very long list: Don't interrupt. \nLet them finish, then say: \"Thanks for sharing all \nof that — I've got it noted. The doctor will review \neverything with you.\"\n\nIf the user mentions something sensitive (mental \nhealth, HIV, past substance use, etc.): Be reassuring \nand neutral: \"Thank you for sharing that — it's all \nconfidential and helps the doctor take better care of \nyou.\"\n\nIf the user can't remember everything: \"No worries — \nwhatever comes to mind is helpful. The intake forms \nwill cover the rest.\"\n\nIf the user says they'd rather share at the visit \nor on the forms: \"Completely fine — we'll get the \nfull picture at your first appointment.\"\n\nIf the user doesn't want to share: \"I understand — \nyou'll have a chance to go through everything with \nthe doctor directly. Let's keep going.\"\n\nOne ask is enough. Do NOT push for a complete medical \nhistory — that's what the visit and forms are for."
      }
    },
